http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The Architectural Design program prepares students to perform entry-level tasks under the supervision and guidance of architects and/or architectural engineers in the development and preparation of plans for residential and/or commercial buildings. These standards are designed to ensure that students will be prepared for postsecondary education and entry-level architectural-related careers.
Maintain a clean, orderly, safe work area.

Select proper drawing equipment to complement the design media.
Demonstrate proper use, care, and adjustment of design equipment.
Draw line symbols using alphabet of lines.
Draw geometric figures using straight and curved lines.
Perform drawing setup to applicable standards (e.g., setting layers, line type, and width).
Identify and use view and display commands (e.g., zoom, pan, viewports, and rotation).
Format, enter, and edit text on a drawing.
Edit, copy, and manipulate drawing entities (e.g., properties, stretch, trimming, and scaling).
Dimension various types of architectural plans and details.
Prepare a window, door, and finish schedule.
Draw related architectural plans (e.g., mechanical, electrical, or civil).
Apply standard building codes to architectural plans.
Identify hardware components of a CAD computer system.
Format disks and copy, delete, rename, save, and back up files and folders.
Identify, create, and use folders and directory structures.
Import and export data files between formats (e.g., IGES and DXF).
Create, retrieve, edit, and use symbol libraries.
Use inquiry commands to extract drawing data (list distance and area).
